VALUES
(40, 22, 13, 44, 7, 54, 54, NULL, 'Weeping and Gnashing Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of gnashing, reflecting intense emotional responses. In Matthew, it signifies punishment, while in Acts, it indicates anger and hostility.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 14, 61, 1, 10, 10, 'called, but few are chosen', 'Calling and Election Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of being chosen and making one''s calling sure. Matthew highlights that while many are called, few are chosen, and 2 Peter urges diligence in confirming one''s election.', 'theme', 0.601, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 14, 42, 13, 23, 24, 'many are called, but few are chosen', 'Connection of Salvation and Choice', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being chosen versus the struggle for salvation. Matthew highlights that while many are called, few are chosen, and Luke underscores that many will seek to enter but will not succeed.', 'theme', 0.5589999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 14, 66, 17, 14, 14, 'for many are called, but few are chosen', 'Called and Chosen Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of being ''called'' and ''chosen.'' Matthew highlights that while many are called, Revelation specifies that those who are with the Lamb are both called and chosen, indicating a deeper commitment.', 'theme', 0.552, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 14, 40, 7, 13, 14, 'few are chosen', 'Connection of Calling and Choosing', 'Both passages emphasize the distinction between many who are called and few who find the narrow way. This connection highlights the theme of exclusivity in salvation, where not all who are invited respond appropriately.', 'theme', 0.5449999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 14, 40, 20, 16, 16, NULL, 'Connection of Calling and Choosing', 'Both passages emphasize the idea that many are called, but few are chosen. This connection highlights a theme of divine selection and the unexpected reversal of roles.', 'theme', 0.482, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 15, 42, 20, 20, 26, 'entangle him in his talk', 'Entanglement in Words', 'Both passages emphasize the attempt to entrap Jesus in his words. In Matthew, the Pharisees seek to ''entangle him in his talk,'' while in Luke, they send spies to ''take hold of his words.'' This connection highlights the ongoing challenge Jesus faced from religious leaders.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 15, 41, 12, 13, 17, 'entangle him in his talk', 'Entanglement in Words', 'Both passages emphasize the attempt to entrap Jesus in his speech. The Pharisees'' strategy to ''entangle him in his talk'' in Matthew aligns with their effort to ''catch him in his words'' in Mark.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 15, 19, 2, 2, 2, 'took counsel', 'Counsel Against the Anointed', 'This connection highlights the theme of rulers taking counsel against God''s anointed. Both passages depict leaders plotting against a significant figure, illustrating a common biblical motif of opposition to divine authority.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 15, 19, 56, 5, 7, 'entangle him in his talk', 'Opposition and Entanglement Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of opposition against a speaker. In Matthew, the Pharisees seek to entangle Jesus in his words, while in Psalms, the psalmist describes how others wrest his words and plot against him.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 15, 23, 29, 21, 21, 'entangle him in his talk', 'Entanglement and Snaring Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the act of laying a snare for someone, highlighting the malicious intent to entrap and accuse. The Pharisees'' attempt to entangle Jesus in his talk mirrors the behavior described in Isaiah of making someone an offender for a word.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 15, 24, 18, 18, 18, 'entangle him in his talk', 'Plot Against Prophets', 'Both passages emphasize a conspiracy to entrap a prophet through words. In Matthew, the Pharisees seek to entangle Jesus in his talk, while in Jeremiah, the plot is to devise devices against him and smite him with the tongue.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 15, 24, 20, 10, 10, 'entangle him in his talk', 'Entanglement and Defamation', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being watched and entangled by others. In Matthew, the Pharisees seek to ''entangle him in his talk,'' while in Jeremiah, the speaker notes that ''all my familiars watched for my halting.''', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 16, 41, 3, 6, 6, NULL, 'Collaboration Against Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the alliance between the Pharisees and Herodians. In Matthew, the Herodians are mentioned alongside the Pharisees'' disciples, while in Mark, they plot together against Jesus.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 16, 41, 8, 15, 15, 'neither carest thou for any man', 'Leaven of Herod and Truth', 'This connection highlights the opposition Jesus faced from both the Pharisees and Herodians, who sought to undermine his teachings. Both passages emphasize the danger of false teachings and the political manipulation represented by Herod.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 16, 42, 20, 21, 21, 'teachest the way of God in truth', 'Connection of Teaching Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the truthfulness of Jesus'' teachings and his impartiality. They highlight that he teaches the way of God truly without regard for individuals.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 16, 18, 32, 21, 22, 'regardest not the person of men', 'Respecting Truth Over Flattery', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of not showing favoritism or giving flattering titles to men. Matthew highlights Jesus'' impartiality in teaching the truth, while Job expresses a commitment to avoid flattery, aligning with the theme of valuing truth over human approval.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 16, 24, 9, 3, 5, 'teachest the way of God in truth', 'Truth and Deception in Speech', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of truth versus lies. Matthew highlights the acknowledgment of truth in Jesus'' teaching, while Jeremiah condemns the deceitful speech of the people. This connection highlights the contrast between genuine truth and the pervasive dishonesty in society.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 16, 43, 7, 18, 18, 'thou art true', 'Truth and Righteousness Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of truth and the integrity of the speaker. In Matthew, Jesus is recognized as true, while in John, the one who seeks the glory of the sender is also described as true.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 16, 43, 14, 6, 6, 'the way of God in truth', 'Connection of Truth and Way', 'This connection highlights the concept of truth and the way to God. In Matthew, Jesus is acknowledged as one who teaches the way of God in truth, while in John, He explicitly states, ''I am the way, the truth, and the life.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 17, 42, 2, 1, 1, 'tribute unto Cesar', 'Tribute and Taxation Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of taxation in both passages. Matthew discusses the legality of paying tribute to Caesar, while Luke mentions a decree from Caesar Augustus for taxation.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 17, 45, 13, 6, 7, 'tribute unto Cesar, or not', 'Tribute and Authority Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of paying tribute to governing authorities. Both passages emphasize the obligation to render what is due to those in power.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 17, 40, 17, 25, 25, 'tribute', 'Tribute and Authority Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of tribute and its relation to authority. In Matthew 22:17, the question of paying tribute to Caesar is posed, while Matthew 17:25 discusses kings taking tribute from strangers, highlighting the theme of who is subject to earthly rulers.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 17, 44, 28, 22, 22, 'What thinkest thou?', 'Questioning Authority and Beliefs', 'This connection highlights the theme of questioning beliefs and authority. Both passages involve inquiries about the legitimacy of certain practices or beliefs, reflecting a tension between societal norms and emerging sects.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 17, 5, 17, 14, 15, NULL, 'Authority and Governance', 'This connection highlights the theme of authority in governance. In Matthew, the question of tribute to Caesar reflects the tension between earthly rulers and divine authority, while Deuteronomy establishes God''s choice in appointing a king, emphasizing the divine mandate in leadership.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 17, 15, 4, 13, 13, 'tribute unto Cesar, or not', 'Tribute and Authority Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of tribute and authority in both passages. Matthew 22:17 questions the lawfulness of paying tribute to Caesar, while Ezra 4:13 warns that the rebuilding of the city will result in a refusal to pay tribute, impacting the king''s revenue.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 17, 15, 7, 24, 24, 'Is it lawful to give tribute', 'Tribute and Lawfulness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of lawfulness regarding tribute. Both passages address the legality of imposing tribute, with Matthew questioning its lawfulness to Caesar and Ezra stating it is not lawful for certain groups.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 18, 42, 5, 22, 22, NULL, 'Perception of Thoughts', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' ability to perceive the thoughts and intentions of others. In Matthew, He identifies the wickedness of His questioners, while in Luke, He discerns the reasoning in their hearts.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 18, 43, 2, 25, 25, 'perceived their wickedness', 'Understanding Human Nature', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' awareness of human motives. Both passages emphasize his insight into the wickedness and intentions of people.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 18, 43, 8, 6, 6, 'tempt ye me, ye hypocrites', 'Temptation and Hypocrisy Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of temptation, with Jesus being confronted by those seeking to trap him. The term ''tempt'' in both contexts highlights the malicious intent of the questioners.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
